commText: Dhoni was complaining about not getting best catch award, but he can't have too many complaints about his team's performance today. The blueprint worked to perfection as CSK got back to winning ways at their home ground after a slip-up against Rajasthan Royals. They've now joined the Royals on four wins, although they're only third on the table because of a lower NRR. So that's all from us here. This is Sagar Chawla signing off on behalf of Harish, Pradeep Krishnamurthy and Saurabh Shankar. Goodnight!

B0$ Coming to Chennai, looking at the wicket gives me a lot of happiness. You know it's going to turn. I had in my mind to not bowl too full. Important to keep wicket to wicket. CSK fans always support us, no matter we win or lose.

B0$ Whatever said and done, last phase of my career, important to enjoy it. It feels good to be here. They have given a lot of love and affection. They always stay late to listen to me. Not getting a lot of chance to bat - I'm not complaining. You need time to pick his action (Pathirana). He has got variation, he has got good pace. We have seen with Malinga - someone who has an awkward action and who is very consistent with line and length - it's difficult to score off him. Definitely he has been a find. I was hesitant to bat second. Had the feeling there won't be much dew. It was slightly cloudy. The spinners, once they came in, they bowled a very good length. Overall the middle overs was the setup. Fast bowlers bowled very well in the last few overs. I always tell them that first preference of field setting is with you. Still they didn't give me best catch award. I was in such a wrong position. Just because we wear gloves, people think it's easy. I felt it was a fantastic catch. Long time back I still remember one game - Rahul Dravid was keeping and he caught one like that. Once you get old, that's the only time you get experience. Unless you're Sachin paaji and start playing at 16-17. Definitely old, can't shy away from that.

B0$ I appreciate it, nice to be there at the end and win it for the team. The plan was simple, we just try to play good cricket shots in the batting PP and put the bowlers under pressure (on the tactics between himself and Gaikwad). We got the best of the conditions honestly, the ball didn't hold as much as it did in the 1st innings, it wasn't the easiest, but was slightly easier (in the second innings). The Bengaluru pitch was a lot better, but we had to play in what was in front of us.

B0$ Disappointed again, never nice to lose. Not good with the bat, couldn’t build partnerships and then you struggle to put a good total. We certainly thought this wasn’t a 130 wicket, it was more around 160. Partnerships weren’t there, we couldn’t build momentum and credit to them for the way they bowled. (On CSK spinners) We knew they’d play a huge role, each person had a plan to counter them - you can either take them down or rotate strike and build partnerships. We had the plans but unfortunately couldn’t execute them. It is about taking on the bowlers in the powerplay, we need to stick to our aggressive approach. We have to look in and see how to get better with the bat, one or two guys need to put their hands up with the bat. Very pleased with the effort from our bowling group.

B0$ Slight frustration towards the end for CSK who would've loved to finish it off sooner. But Mayank Markande bowled a lovely spell, continuing his good form with the ball. The result was hardly ever in doubt though. Markande delayed the inevitable, but CSK had it covered after another fantastic start provided by Devon Conway and Ruturaj Gaikwad. What a brilliant opening combo they've been. The two of them put on 87 for the for the first wicket, and were only separated because of an unfortunate run out which sent Gaikwad packing. Conway, though, kicked on past fifty to finish unbeaten and get his team home. SRH just didn't have enough runs on the board today, with Ravindra Jadeja leading a brilliant effort from the CSK bowlers. He was complimented nicely by Maheesh Theekshana and Matheesha Pathirana as the visitors managed just 58 runs in the final 10 overs.

B0$ On a slightly two-paced wicket, SRH have huffed and puffed their way to 134. On such a pitch, they needed their openers to give them a fast start - they sent Abhishek Sharma to open and he responded with a 26-ball 34, Harry Brook got a start, but the innings stalled with the introduction of spin. Ravindra Jadeja made most of the slowness of the surface, the ball gripped and turned and he made life miserable for the SRH's middle-order batters, rewarded with three wickets. He was well supported by Maheesh Theekshana and SRH's lower order struggled to pick Pathirana's variations. 10 overs of spin and CSK dominated that phase with 4 for 62. Can SRH's spinners get the same kind of help in the 2nd innings, they'll need to, else the target of 135 could be a stroll in the park for CSK's batters. Back shortly for the chase..

Sunrisers Hyderabad have had a full roller of a season thus far, as they were thumped in their first two games, but then claimed a resounding victory against Punjab Kings, followed by a Harry Brook century that got them over the line at Eden Gardens. Then, they were beaten by MI on their own patch so form has been all over the place for SRH. They do have a very strong team on paper, but unless their Indian players like Mayank Agarwal, Washington Sundar, Umran Malik and Rahul Tripathi start pulling their weight, they are going to struggle. It is a slightly cloudy evening at Chepauk, so we might have to keep an eye out on the weather as well today. Stick on for the toss and other updates

CSK almost never lose at Chepauk but as luck may have it, they did lose their previous home game at Rajasthan but have made up for it with wins on the road in Mumbai and Bangalore. What has worked for them so far has been their batting, with either Ruturaj and Conway scoring big almost every game, while Shivam Dube and Ajinkya Rahane enjoy a rather unexpected career renaissance this IPL. Their death bowling has also risen with every passing game, with Tushar Deshpande and the inclusion of Pathirana covering most bases.
